Feature: the bc-base image bakes the external operator CLIs gh, docker, and agent-vault onto PATH

  Pins lead-qi0q (product-authority request, dave 2026-06-10). A BC agent
  invokes three external operator CLIs at runtime: "gh" (GitHub operations),
  "docker" (container operations), and "agent-vault" (the credential-broker
  wrapper, e.g. "agent-vault run -- claude" per scenario 45). The request is
  to pin that all three are PRESENT and resolvable on PATH in the published
  bc-base image — the image guarantees these three CLIs are invocable.

  Three presence facts motivate the pin, per the request:
  - "gh" is present today only INCIDENTALLY from the upstream base image and
    could silently regress. This scenario makes "gh on PATH" a TESTED
    guarantee of the bc-base image rather than an incidental property, so the
    Architect's Dockerfile work must install gh as an explicit/pinned dep, not
    rely on the base image continuing to ship it.
  - "docker" (the client) is MISSING from bc-base today and must be added.
  - "agent-vault" is installed (prior work) but carries no presence-pin of its
    own; scenario 51 (@scenario_hash 938342272de4e38a) asserts it resolves on
    PATH only incidentally, in the bootstrap-entrypoint-mode context. This
    scenario pins agent-vault presence as a first-class bc-base guarantee
    (overlaps 51 on agent-vault — Architect to dedupe at register time).

  SCOPE: presence-and-invocability on PATH in the IMAGE only. This file does
  NOT pin the docker SOCKET mount / --group-add behavior (that is the
  Architect's socket-mount POLICY decision; the launcher-side socket-group
  behavior is already pinned by templates scenario 198), and does NOT pin how
  the Dockerfile installs each CLI (the install recipe and the gh
  explicit-pin shape are the Architect's at dispatch). The CLIs need only be
  invocable enough to report their own version, which does not require an
  external daemon, broker, or credential. (Targets shopsystem-bc-launcher.)

  ARCHITECT DISPATCH INSTRUCTION (lead-qi0q, ADR-044):
  - Add the "docker" CLI (the docker client) to the bc-base Dockerfile — it is
    MISSING today. Image-presence only; the client need only run "docker
    --version" without a reachable daemon.
  - Install "gh" as an EXPLICIT, PINNED dependency in the bc-base Dockerfile;
    do NOT rely on the upstream base image continuing to ship it (today it is
    incidental and could silently regress).
  - Keep "agent-vault" resolvable on PATH (already installed via prior work).
  - SOCKET POLICY (ADR-044): host docker-socket access is OPT-IN PER BC, not
    fleet-wide. The bc-base IMAGE only bakes the docker CLI; the socket grant
    (the /var/run/docker.sock bind mount + the --group-add of the socket's
    owning group resolved via "stat -L -c '%g' /var/run/docker.sock") stays a
    LAUNCH-TIME concern, already pinned by features/bc-launcher/54
    (@scenario_hash ff370a4e7e9dac5e opt-in mount / e177655ba09a73fa default no
    mount) and features/templates/198 (@scenario_hash 84a32b05666d9e82, the
    symmetric --group-add grant). Do NOT bake any socket grant into the image.
    shopsystem-bc-launcher is the first non-lead opt-in consumer (it needs the
    socket to run real launch integration tests instead of the FakeDockerDriver),
    but that wiring is launch-time work pinned by 54/198, NOT part of this
    image-presence pin.

  @bc:shopsystem-bc-launcher @scenario_hash:63ed6ac34b8bd64c
  Scenario: a container run from the published bc-base image resolves gh, docker, and agent-vault on PATH
    Given a container is run from the published "ghcr.io/dstengle/shopsystem-bc-base:latest" image
    When "gh", "docker", and "agent-vault" are each resolved on PATH inside that container
    Then "gh" resolves to an executable on PATH and a "gh --version" invocation exits zero without contacting any external service
    And "docker" resolves to an executable on PATH and a "docker --version" invocation exits zero without requiring a reachable docker daemon
    And "agent-vault" resolves to an executable on PATH and an "agent-vault --version" invocation exits zero without requiring a reachable broker
